# Main Notes

## Trade Fixed Expense for Variable Expense

Traditional on-premises infrastructure requires a large upfront investment to purchase servers, networking equipment, storage, buildings, cooling systems, and hire IT staff. These are fixed expenses because they must be paid regardless of how much the infrastructure is used.

AWS changes this model by allowing businesses to rent IT resources and pay only for what they actually use. This converts fixed expenses into variable expenses, reducing financial risk and allowing businesses to invest saved money into product development, marketing, hiring, or business growth.

---

## Benefit from Massive Economies of Scale

Economies of Scale means the cost per item becomes lower when purchasing in large quantities.

AWS buys servers, networking equipment, storage devices, and hardware in massive quantities. Because of this, hardware manufacturers offer AWS lower prices.

AWS passes part of these savings to customers, allowing even small startups to access enterprise-level infrastructure at affordable prices.

---

## Stop Guessing Capacity

In traditional data centers, businesses had to predict future demand before buying infrastructure.

If they overestimated demand, they wasted money on unused servers.

If they underestimated demand, their applications could become slow or unavailable, leading to poor customer experience.

AWS eliminates this problem by allowing businesses to provision resources whenever needed and remove them when demand decreases.

---

## Scalability

Scalability is the ability of a system to increase or decrease its capacity by adding or removing resources.

It answers the question:

Can the system grow or shrink to handle changing workloads?

Example:
A shopping website normally handles 1,000 users. During a festival sale it receives 50,000 users. More servers can be added to increase capacity.

Scalability can increase or decrease resources depending on business needs.

---

## Elasticity

Elasticity is the ability of a system to automatically add or remove resources based on real-time demand.

It answers the question:

Can resource changes happen automatically without manual intervention?

Example:
A website receives a sudden traffic spike at midnight. AWS automatically launches additional servers and removes them after traffic decreases.

---

## Increase Speed and Agility

AWS allows businesses to create infrastructure within minutes instead of waiting weeks or months for physical hardware.

Businesses can quickly build, test, modify, deploy, and delete applications without making large upfront investments.

This allows companies to innovate faster and respond quickly to changing customer needs.

---

## Stop Spending Money Running and Maintaining Data Centers

Businesses no longer need to manage physical infrastructure themselves.

AWS is responsible for:
- Physical servers
- Storage hardware
- Networking equipment
- Cooling systems
- Power supply
- Hardware replacement
- Physical security

Businesses can focus on building applications instead of maintaining infrastructure.

---

## Go Global in Minutes

AWS has infrastructure around the world.

Businesses can deploy applications in AWS Regions close to their customers without building their own data centers in every country.

This reduces expansion time from months or years to minutes while improving customer experience through lower latency.

