MAIN NOTES

1. High Availability
- High Availability means keeping an application accessible with minimal downtime even if one component fails.
- AWS achieves this by distributing resources across multiple Availability Zones and Regions.

2. Fault Tolerance
- Fault Tolerance means a system continues operating even if multiple components fail.
- AWS designs its infrastructure to handle failures without affecting customer applications.

3. AWS Regions
- AWS Regions are physical geographic locations around the world.
- Each Region contains multiple Availability Zones.
- Regions help businesses achieve low latency, global expansion, and disaster recovery.

4. Availability Zones (AZs)
- Availability Zones are isolated infrastructure locations inside an AWS Region.
- Each AZ contains one or more data centers.
- AZs have independent power, networking, and connectivity.

5. Redundancy
- Redundancy means keeping backup infrastructure and resources so applications remain available during failures.

6. Why AWS Created AZs
- AWS engineers identified that placing all infrastructure in a single building creates a single point of failure.
- Physical isolation reduces the risk of simultaneous failures.

